content.the_containing_block_trap_fixed_position:
Several background bug #77143569 on Stack Overflow pinpoints the second-most-common React failure mode: a developer applied `backdrop-filter` to an ancestor of a modal scrim and `position: fixed` stopped pinning to the viewport [the_containing_block_trap_fixed_positioning_stops_pinning[0]] [3]. The thread quotes the spec rule that "the filter forms a containing-block for its child" and frames the cascade: `transform`, `filter`, `backdrop-filter`, and `perspective` all act as containing-block creators. The accepted fix is to push the filter onto a `::before` or `::after` pseudo-element so the host element keeps its real containing block hierarchy [the_containing_block_trap_fixed_positioning_stops_pinning[0]] [3].

A concrete pattern for preserving `position: fixed` descendants:

```css
.scrim-host { position: relative; /* no filter on this element */ }
.scrim-host::before {
  content: "";
  position: absolute;
  inset: 0;
  background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.5);
  backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
  -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
  z-index: -1;
}
```

The pseudo-element carries the filter while the host stays free of any property that would create a containing block, so nested `position: fixed` children keep pinning to the viewport (or to the nearest non-filtered ancestor). Rolandixor's "four-piece pseudo-element technique" packages this idea as a portability play: parent `position: relative`, child pseudo with `content: ""`, `position: absolute`, `inset: 0`, `z-index: -1`, and `filter: blur(18px)` instead of `backdrop-filter` [the_containing_block_trap_fixed_positioning_stops_pinning[1]] [44]. The `filter` form works in IE and Firefox builds that lacked `backdrop-filter`, but it blurs the painted pseudo-element (not the live content behind it), so it is a portability-vs-accuracy trade-off.

| Approach | What gets blurred | `position: fixed` children still pinned? | Best when |
|---|---|---|---|
| `backdrop-filter` on host | True backdrop (live content behind) | No (host becomes containing block) | Static layout, no fixed descendants |
| `backdrop-filter` on `::before` pseudo | True backdrop | Yes | Modal scrims, sticky navs |
| `filter: blur()` on `::before` pseudo with `z-index: -1` | Painted copy of content beneath | Yes (pseudo-element carries it) | Legacy Firefox / IE fallback |

Takeaway: split the host from the filter when fixed descendants or scroll-driven transforms must coexist with the blur.

content.performance_budget_and_layer_promotion_i:
Mavik Labs' "CSS Backdrop-Filter Performance in 2026: Blur Effects Without the Jank" gives the most current numerical guidance for shipping frosted glass [performance_budget_and_layer_promotion_in_2026[0]] [34]:

- Blur radius 8-16px is "generally considered safe."
- Blur radius >20px "requires careful testing."
- Blur radius >32px "is expected to cause issues on some devices."
- GPU-layer promotion can be forced with `transform: translateZ(0)` and `backface-visibility: hidden`.
- `will-change: transform` should be used sparingly: "overuse can lead to memory pressure and worsen performance."
- Animating the blur radius directly is expensive. The recommended pattern is to "animate the `opacity` of a pre-blurred element or use a blurred static pseudo-element."
- Safari on iOS 26 has experienced bugs that break web layouts for "fixed or sticky positioning," even when the filter itself is at fault.

Mechanism: backdrop-filter has to snapshot the painted pixels behind the host, blur them on the GPU, and re-composite with each frame. The cost scales with the blur radius squared and the pixel count blurred. Promoting the host to its own layer (`will-change`, `transform: translateZ(0)`) keeps the snapshot from being invalidated by sibling paints, but every layer you create consumes GPU memory; overuse is the modern equivalent of memory bloat.

The MDN backdrop-filter page classifies the property as Baseline 2024 [performance_budget_and_layer_promotion_in_2026[1]] [6], meaning the unprefixed form works across the latest devices and browser versions. The practical reality in mid-2026 still requires the `-webkit-` prefix for Safari because Safari has historically gated backdrop-filter behind WebKit prefixes, despite shipping the standard form as well [performance_budget_and_layer_promotion_in_2026[0]] [34].

A pragmatic shipping recipe:

```css
.glass {
  background: hsl(0deg 0% 100% / 0.95); /* opaque fallback */
  transition: background 200ms ease;
}
@supports (backdrop-filter: blur(1px)) or (-webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(1px)) {
  .glass {
    background: hsl(0deg 0% 100% / 0.5);
    backdrop-filter: blur(12px) saturate(140%);
    -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(12px) saturate(140%);
  }
}
```
